>>180223722
Fate was never about fighting for grails or about servants, this is what GO gets wrong. What made F/SN good were the themes about morality and self sacrifice vs selfishness. Shirou's development, the exploration of his twisted worldview and his dynamic with Kirei and Archer. The best characters in F/SN are Shirou Emiya, Kirei Kotomine, Kiritsugu and Archer (nameless hero) for this reason.

This is also why F/Z is the only good direct spin off of FSN, because it understood what made F/SN good and built upon it. There is no theme or depth to Zero that wasn't explored in FSN prior. Uncomfortable as you may be with the idea, but Urobuchi wrote Zero to expand on the backstory that already explored the majority of what it had to say provided in FSN.

The 3 main focal points of Fate/Zero are kiritsugu's morality (and how it contrasts with Shirou's), Kotomine awakening to his true nature (which finally made Gil an interesting character instead of the Saber orbiter/Psychopath, because all he was in UBW was a psycho), and Saber's idea of kingship vs Rider and Gilgamesh's.

Diarmuid Ua Duibhne (Zero Lancer) is handsome and charming and he reminds Arthur of one of her knights, someone she was very close to, she is in a good mood and lad banter feels right. Lancelot (Zero Berserker) is plagiarized from Diarmud's legend. Arthur treats Diarmuid Ua Duibhne different from every other servant because in a way they are not strangers. Lancelot and Diarmuid Ua Duibhne team up to fight Arthur a few pages later so even the people that are maybe not as smart get this spelled out for them.

Every other spinoff of Fate has always made the critical error of focusing on the idea of servants, and they've had some pretty cool ones like Vlad and Karna, but they all lack the thematic linchpin that actual makes the story worth reading.

>>180222884
In a general sense it's just better written. You can't boil it down to bullet points, it's a consistently higher level of craft in all details.

But if you needed big, easy things to point to I think a huge thing to me is that Fate/Zero actually delivered on the premise of the Grail War and made it feel real because the contestants were actual fucking adults with the seriousness and sense of stakes of adults. It much more convincingly presented itself as a world-defining shadow war between real life modern day sorcerers, because they took it that seriously and were as ruthless as you would actually be with that much on the line.

Them being adults also sold the interpersonal drama better. These are people with actual histories and resentments and fixations born of experiences that took place over substantial amounts of time.

But more than that it did not subordinate itself to anti-versimillitude fanservice and high school bullshit. Saber consistently acts like she actually lived a life as a warrior and a political figure with a misguided martyr complex. She is not cute or shy around a teenage boy. People in Fate/Zero act like they have the background and life experience they're meant to, and act like they're competing for something world-changing.

One contestant is a teenager and he's forced to deal with the situation seriously and has an actual arc with an adult mentor. It fits. The most unrealistic main character is how quixotic and idealistic Kitsurigo is. But at least they gave him a background where he never had any sense of normality, tragedy he could remember and habituation to risking his life. As opposed to Shirou going to school and having a nice upbringing. And then once again Kitsuragi actually acted like he want to win, he wasn't nearly as unrealistically and shallowly rigid as Shirou

I absolutely loved this show, and it grieves me to know that we truly will never get another show of this magnitude. I can only imagine what it would have been like to see how the filmmakers would have handled Caligula, then the subdued Claudius, and then Domitian, the reign of Trajan and Hadrian, then the fall of the Pax Romana with Marcus Aurelius' reign, the shitshow that was the Severan Dynasty, the clusterfuck of the third century, the TRVE OPTIMVS PRINCEPS IMPERATOR CAESAR AURELIANVS AVGVSTVS, CONSTANTINVS MAGNVS, and other retards like Theodosius and Valentinian III.
I suppose the reason why it'll never be done is because there's just so much more context to the Dominate/later Roman period, granted the dying days of the Republic are still tumultuous, but they're a lot more open, everyone knows at least the basics of Caesar's rise to power and his glory, but barring MAYBE Nero, I doubt most people even know who comes after until Constantine, after which their knowledge probably gets into abyss levels.
Either way, XIII!

>>Extremely well written character arcs and moments
Having just watched this show for the first time a couple months ago, I don't agree with this at all. The only good "character arcs" were the ones lifted from history. Verenus was a good character, stern but upright, until whispering about his cuckoldry became the kink that made Julius Caeser's assassination possible. From there to the wife's suicide to the children banishment to the black-shirt "I am the son of hades fear me!" tavern to the sister-in-law runaway to the children rescue to "my father saved us so I hate him and want him dead please have sex with me, sexy doll maker" to literally just fuck all that. All of it. Octavian was oddly written throughout, jumping from meek pushover to bold master tactician between scenes, then after the timeskip he solidifies as an absolute waste of screentime. The House Brutus woman I can't remember the name of going full psychopath over Julius doing his job was even more ridiculous, and she became less bearable the longer she stayed alive, until the jew mysteriously decided that the psychopath being abused is too far, even though all the innocents he murdered, tortured, and raped was fine.

The good ones were the ones from history. Mark Anthony, Cicero, Julius. Pullo had good moments, but also a lot of bad ones, especially when they wanted him to play the part of "simpleton" instead of "simple man" without any real consistency.

I liked the show a lot, but the second season practically feels like a fever dream with how poorly all those character arcs go in it. Even Anthony, a pillar of the show, becomes a drunk idiot by the end once the writers liberally tweak history for his demise. It would be a 10/10 if it had just ended with Julius Caesar's death.
